{"100":{"department":"CEE","number":"100","title":"Managing Sustainable Building Projects","description":"Managing the life cycle of buildings from the owner, designer, and contractor perspectives emphasizing sustainability goals; methods to define, communicate, coordinate, and manage multidisciplinary project objectives including scope, quality, life cycle cost and value, schedule, safety, energy, and social concerns; roles, responsibilities, and risks for project participants; virtual design and construction methods for product, organization, and process modeling; lifecycle assessment methods; individual writing assignment related to a real world project.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103449,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fischer, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Fischer, M."],"location":"160-124"}],"id":16153}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"101A":{"department":"CEE","number":"101A","title":"Mechanics of Materials","description":"Introduction to beam and column theory. Normal stress and strain in beams under various loading conditions; shear stress and shear flow; deflections of determinate and indeterminate beams; analysis of column buckling; structural loads in design; strength and serviceability criteria. Lab experiments. Prerequisites: ENGR 14.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103450,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Linder, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Linder, C."],"location":"McMurtry Building rm 350"}],"id":28031}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"101C":{"department":"CEE","number":"101C","title":"Geotechnical Engineering","description":"Introduction to the principles of soil mechanics. Soil classification, shear strength and stress-strain behavior of soils, consolidation theory, analysis and design of earth retaining structures, introduction to shallow and deep foundation design, slope stability. Lab projects. Prerequisite: ENGR 14. Recommended: 101A.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103452,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Borja, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Borja, R."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":16154}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"101D":{"department":"CEE","number":"101D","title":"Computations in Civil and Environmental Engineering (CEE 201D)","description":"Computational and visualization methods in the design and analysis of civil and environmental engineering systems. Focus is on applications of MATLAB. How to develop a more lucid and better organized programming style.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103453,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15310}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"101N":{"department":"CEE","number":"101N","title":"Mechanics of Fluids (with lab)","description":"Combination of CEE 101B and CEE 160 as a new four unit course. CEE 101B and CEE 160 will be taught separately, for the last time, during Spring in the 2015-16 academic year.  Thereafter, CEE's undergraduate Mechanics of Fluids class will be taught in its new combined format only, in Autumn quarter.  Students seeking to take this class without the laboratory should enroll in 3 units of CEE 101X.  Prerequisites: E14, Physics 14, Math 51.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":217010,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Ouellette, N."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,true,true,true,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Ouellette, N."],"location":"Turingaud"}],"id":28789}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"101X":{"department":"CEE","number":"101X","title":"Mechanics of Fluids (No Lab)","description":"Combination of CEE 101B and CEE 160 as a new four unit course.  CEE 101B and CEE 160 will be taught separately, for the last time, during Spring in the 2015-16 academic year.  Thereafter, CEE's undergraduate Mechanics of Fluids class will be taught in its new combined format only, in Autumn quarter.  Students seeking to take this class with the laboratory should enroll in 4  units of CEE 101N.  Prerequisites: E14, Physics 14, Math 51.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":217003,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Ouellette, N."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,true,true,true,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Ouellette, N."],"location":""}],"id":28784}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"102":{"department":"CEE","number":"102","title":"Legal Principles in Design, Construction, and Project Delivery","description":"Introduction to the key legal principles affecting design, construction and the delivery of infrastructure projects. The course begins with an introduction to the structure of law, including principles of contract, negligence, professional responsibility, intellectual property, land use and environmental law, then draws on these concepts to examine current and developing means of project delivery.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103455,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Ashcraft, H."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Ashcraft, H."],"location":"Thornt211"}],"id":28032}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"107A":{"department":"CEE","number":"107A","title":"Understanding Energy (CEE 207A, EARTHSYS 103)","description":"Energy is one of the world's main drivers of opportunity and development for human beings. At the same time, our energy system has significant consequences for our society, political system, economy, and environment. For example, energy production and use is the #1 source of greenhouse gas emissions. This course surveys key aspects of each energy resource, including significance and potential conversion processes and technologies, drivers and barriers, policy and regulatory environment, and social, economic, and environmental impacts. Both depletable and renewable energy resources are covered, including oil, natural gas, coal, nuclear, biomass, hydroelectric, wind, solar, photovoltaics, geothermal, and ocean energy, with cross-cutting topics including electricity, storage, climate change, sustainability, green buildings, energy efficiency, transportation, and the developing world. Understanding Energy is part of a trio of inter-related courses aimed at gaining an in-depth understanding of each energy resource - from fossil fuels to renewable energy. The other two classes are CEE107W/207W Understanding Energy - Workshop, and CEE 107F/207F Understanding Energy -- Field Trips.  Note that this course was formerly called Energy Resources (CEE 173A/207A & Earthsys 103). Prerequisites: Algebra. May not be taken for credit by students who have completed CEE 107S.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":129085,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Knapp, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Grubert, E.","Knapp, K.","Woodward, J.","Ginnebaugh, D."],"location":"Cubberley Auditorium"}],"id":15995}],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"107F":{"department":"CEE","number":"107F","title":"Understanding Energy -- Field Trips (CEE 207F)","description":"Understanding Energy -- Field Trips takes students on trips to some of the most significant energy resource sites in North American located within a few hours of Stanford University. Students visit at least two of the many field trips offered, including to Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant, an Altmont Pass wind farm, a geothermal facility at The Geysers, a solar photovoltaic (PV) farm, Shasta Dam and hydroelectric power plant, a major oil field, and a natural gas-fired power plant, an energy efficiency technology lab, among others. Students meet on a weekly basis to debrief previous field trips and prepare for future ones. Open to all majors and backgrounds. Understanding Energy Field Trips is part of a trio of inter-related courses aimed at gaining an in-depth understanding of each energy resource -- from fossil fuels to renewable energy. The other two classes are CEE 107A/207A Understanding Energy, and CEE 107W/207W Understanding Energy - Workshop. Priority is given to students who have taken or are concurrently enrolled in CEE 173A, CEE 107A, CEE 207A, Earthsys 103, or CEE 107S/207S.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217151,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Knapp, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Knapp, K."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":29032}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Activity"},
"10A":{"department":"CEE","number":"10A","title":"Introduction to Architecture","description":"This class introduces students to the discipline of architecture and to the fundamental question: What is an architect and how is architecture distinct from other arts and sciences?  To answer this question, the class will focus on concepts important to the practice of architecture including: project conception, drawing, modeling, materials, structure, form, and professionalism. These terms will be investigated through short talks, site visits, historical precedent, in-class exercises, panel discussions and two on-campus case studies.  No prior knowledge of architecture is required.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":215007,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Barton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Barton, J."],"location":""}],"id":45979}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"112A":{"department":"CEE","number":"112A","title":"Industry Applications of Virtual Design & Construction","description":"Building upon the concept of VDC Scorecard, CEE 112A/212A investigates in the management of Virtual Design and Construction (VDC) programs and projects in the building industry. Interacting with experts and professionals in real estate, architecture, engineering, construction and technology providers, students will learn from the industry applications of Building Information Modeling and its relationship with Integrated Project Delivery, Sustainable Design and Construction. Students will conduct case studies to evaluate the maturity of VDC planning, adoption, technology and performance in practice. Students taking 3 or 4 units will be paired up with independent research or case study projects on the industry applications of VDC. No prerequisite. See CEE112B/212B in the Winter Quarter and CEE 112C/212C in the Spring Quarter.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":212503,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kam, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"7:30:00 PM","end":"9:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kam, C."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":33866}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"120A":{"department":"CEE","number":"120A","title":"Building Information Modeling Workshop (CEE 220A)","description":"The foundational Building Information Modeling course introduces techniques for creating, managing, and applying of building information models in the building design and construction process. The course covers processes and tools for creating, organizing, and working with 2D and 3D computer representations of building components and geometries to produce models used in architectural design, construction planning and documentation, rendering and visualization, simulation and analysis.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215127,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":28601},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15741}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"120B":{"department":"CEE","number":"120B","title":"Building Information Modeling Workshop (CEE 220B)","description":"This course builds upon the Building Information Model concepts introduced in 120A/220A and illustrates how BIM modeling tools are used to design, analyze, and model building systems including structural, mechanical, electrical, plumbing and fire protection. Course covers the physical principles, design criteria, and design strategies for each system and explores processes and tools for modeling those systems and analyzing their performance.nTopics include: building envelopes, access systems, structural systems modeling and analysis, mechanical / HVAC systems, plumbing and fire protection systems, electrical systems, and systems integration/coordination.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215128,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":30416}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":46373},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15937}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"122A":{"department":"CEE","number":"122A","title":"Computer Integrated Architecture/Engineering/Construction (A/E/C)","description":"Undergraduates serve as apprentices to graduate students in the AEC global project teams in CEE 222A. Apprentices participate in all activities of the AEC team, including the goals, objectives, constraints, tasks, and process of a crossdisciplinary global AEC teamwork in the concept development phase of a comprehensive building project. Prerequisite: consent of instructor.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":103468,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"location":""}],"id":28033},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"12:03:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"location":""}],"id":46341}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"125":{"department":"CEE","number":"125","title":"Defining Smart Cities: Visions of Urbanism for the 21st Century (CEE 225, URBANST 174)","description":"In a rapidly urbanizing world, \"the city\" paves the way toward sustainability and social well-being. But what does it mean for a city to be smart? Does that also make it sustainable or resilient or livable? This seminar delves into current debates about urbanism through weekly talks by experts on topics such as big data, human-centered design, new urbanism, and natural capital. How urban spaces are shaped, for better or worse, by the complex interaction of cutting-edge technology, human societies, and the natural environment. The goal is to provoke vigorous discussion and to foster an understanding of cities that is at once technological, humanistic, and ecologically sound.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":216985,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Law, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hsu, K.","Chan, D.","Law, K."],"location":"160-124"}],"id":28739}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"126":{"department":"CEE","number":"126","title":"International Urbanization Seminar: Cross-Cultural Collaboration for Sustainable Urban Development (EARTHSYS 138, IPS 274, URBANST 145)","description":"Comparative approach to sustainable cities, with focus on international practices and applicability to China. Tradeoffs regarding land use, infrastructure, energy and water, and the need to balance economic vitality, environmental quality, cultural heritage, and social equity.  Student teams collaborate with Chinese faculty and students partners to support urban sustainability projects. Limited enrollment via application; see internationalurbanization.org for details. Prerequisites: consent of the instructor(s).","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":214981,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Chan, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hsu, K.","Chan, D."],"location":"50-52E"}],"id":28598}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"130":{"department":"CEE","number":"130","title":"Architectural Design: 3-D Modeling, Methodology, and Process","description":"Preference to Architectural Design majors; others by consent of instructor. Projects investigate conceptual approaches to the design of key architectural elements, such as wall and roof. Functional and structural considerations. Focus is on constructing 3-D models in a range of materials; 3-D computer modeling. Students keep a graphic account of the evolution of their design process. Final project entails design of a simple structure. Limited enrollment. Pre- or corequisite: CEE 31 or 31Q.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["WAY-CE"],"id":202111,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Choe, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Choe, B."],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":16049}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"131B":{"department":"CEE","number":"131B","title":"Financial Management of Sustainable Urban Systems","description":"Focus is on financial management of sustainable urban systems. The course will study different kinds of financial services available, the management of financial resources, and relationships to financial service providers. The course will also study how financial services and relationships to financial service providers can be used to accomplish construction management, energy, and architecture work in sustainable urban systems. The learning outcome is an understanding of how financial services can be used in development of sustainable urban systems.  nnThe course work is structured so that there are three modules: 1) general knowledge of financial management, 2) in-depth application in construction management, energy, or architecture, and 3) comparison of similarities and differences in-between the in-depth applications. Students will focus on one of the in-depth applications in a group work, and present the result of this application to students that make other applications. A key learning aspect is the understanding of how finance is used in construction management, energy, and architecture work.  Students should be able to show the value, financial viability, and risk management of sustainable urban system development in construction management, energy, and architecture. Students should be able to finance construction management, energy, and architecture work. nnReadings include applications of finance and management to construction management, energy, or architecture. Guest speakers include developers, financial managers at construction firms, managers at energy firms, construction managers.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216222,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Eriksson, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Eriksson, K."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 108"}],"id":46047}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"133F":{"department":"CEE","number":"133F","title":"Principles of Freehand Drawing","description":"Traditional methods of depicting shape, form, and surface are applied to the discipline of architectural drawing. Students develop abilities to observe visual phenomenon analytically and translate subjects onto a two-dimensional surface  in a variety of media. Drawing techniques such as modeling form, shading, rendering materials, and articulating landscaping are explored.  Linear perspective exercises provide a foundation for the construction of drawings to illustrate cohesive design proposals. Step-by-step constructions, quick freehand sketches from slides, and on-location studies.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":210743,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Azgour, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"7:20:00 PM","instructors":["Azgour, M."],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":45908}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"133G":{"department":"CEE","number":"133G","title":"Architectural History & Drawing in Eastern Europe","description":"Students in this seminar will travel to Prague, Czech Republic and Krakow, Poland for a week of historical morning walks and discussions about architectural and urbanism in each city. Afternoon sketching sessions will focus attention on some of the locations visited earlier that day. Buildings, sites and monuments from the Middle Ages to the present will be assessed, questioned, and drawn. Short reading assignments and/or films provide a background for each day's examination of a section of these two cities. Possible day trips may include site visits to Auschwitz and the Wieliczka Salt Mine. Casual late afternoon excursions will complement themes of the course. Upon returning to Stanford, the seminar will meet four times to discuss observations and organize a small exhibition of the sketches made during the trip.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":217134,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Azgour, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,true],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Azgour, M.","Beischer, T."],"location":"Y2E2 335"}],"id":28835}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"134B":{"department":"CEE","number":"134B","title":"Intermediate Arch Studio (CEE 234B)","description":"This studio offers students experience in working with a real site and a real client program to develop a community facility. Students will develop site analysis, review a program for development and ultimately design their own solutions that meet client and community goals. Sustainability, historic preservation, community needs and materials will all play a part in the development of students final project. Students will also gain an understanding of graphic conventions, verbal and presentation techniques. Course may be repeated for credit.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":208667,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Barton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Barton, J.","Shiles, B."],"location":""}],"id":15671}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"6:00:00 PM","end":"8:50:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":15440}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"141A":{"department":"CEE","number":"141A","title":"Infrastructure Project Development (CEE 241A)","description":"Infrastructure is critical to the economy, global competitiveness and quality of life. Topics include energy, transportation, water, public facilities, and communications sectors. Analysis of the condition of the nation's infrastructure and how projects are planned and financed. Focus is on public works in the U.S. The role of public and private sectors through a step-by-step study of the project development process. Case studies of real infrastructure projects. Industry guest speakers. Student teams prepare project environmental impact statements.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":210192,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":"380-380X"}],"id":15709}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"156":{"department":"CEE","number":"156","title":"Building Systems (CEE 256)","description":"HVAC, lighting, and envelope systems for commercial and institutional buildings, with a focus on energy efficient design. Knowledge and skills required in the development of low-energy buildings that provide high quality environment for occupants.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103488,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kolderup, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kolderup, E."],"location":"300-300"}],"id":33291}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"163E":{"department":"CEE","number":"163E","title":"International Climate Negotiations: Unpacking the Road to Paris (CEE 263E, EARTHSYS 163E, EARTHSYS 263E)","description":"Interested in what's going on with international climate negotiations, why it has proven so difficult to reach a meaningful agreement? Wondering whether or not another UN agreement is even a meaningful part of climate policy in 2015? This course traces the history of climate negotiations from the very first awareness of the problem of climate change, through the Kyoto Protocol and Copenhagen Accord, to the current state of international negotiations in the lead-up to the 21st Conference of the Parties meeting in Paris in December 2015. The course covers fundamental concepts in climate change science and policy, international law and multilateral environmental agreements, as well as key issues of climate finance, climate justice, equity, adaptation, communication, and social movements that together comprise the subjects of debate in the negotiations. We will discuss all the key facets of what&iquest;s being negotiated in Paris and prepare students to follow the outcome of the negotiation in detail. Students also participate in a three-day mock conference of the parties. By application only.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216942,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Strong, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Tangri, N.","Nevle, R.","Strong, A."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":28718}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"163F":{"department":"CEE","number":"163F","title":"Groundwork for COP21 (CEE 263F, EARTHSYS 163F, EARTHSYS 263F)","description":"This course will prepare undergraduate and coterm students to participate in the climate change negotiations (COP 21) in Paris in November/December 2015. Students will develop individual projects to be carried out before and during the negotiation session and be paired with graduate student mentors. Please note: Along with EARTHSYS 163E/CEE 163E, this course is part of the required two-course-set in which undergraduate and co-terminal masters degree students must enroll to receive accreditation to the climate negotiations.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217077,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Tangri, N."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"6:00:00 PM","end":"7:20:00 PM","instructors":["Strong, A.","Nevle, R.","Cina, S.","Tangri, N."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":29038}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"166A":{"department":"CEE","number":"166A","title":"Watersheds and Wetlands (CEE 266A)","description":"Introduction to the occurrence and movement of water in the natural environment and its role in creating and maintaining terrestrial, wetland, and aquatic habitat. Hydrologic processes, including precipitation, evaporation, transpiration, snowmelt, infiltration, subsurface flow, runoff, and streamflow. Rivers and lakes, springs and swamps. Emphasis is on observation and measurement, data analysis, modeling, and prediction. Prerequisite: 101B or equivalent. (Freyberg)","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":202123,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["MacVean, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["MacVean, L."],"location":"200-305"}],"id":15332}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"166B":{"department":"CEE","number":"166B","title":"Floods and Droughts, Dams and Aqueducts (CEE 266B)","description":"Sociotechnical systems associated with human use of water as a resource and the hazards posed by too much or too little water. Potable and non-potable water use and conservation. Irrigation, hydroelectric power generation, rural and urban water supply systems, storm water management, flood damage mitigation, and water law and institutions. Emphasis is on engineering design. Prerequisite: 166A or equivalent. (Freyberg)","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":202124,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":28095}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"171":{"department":"CEE","number":"171","title":"Environmental Planning Methods","description":"For juniors and seniors. Use of microeconomics and mathematical optimization theory in the design of environmental regulatory programs; tradeoffs between equity and efficiency in designing regulations; techniques for predicting adverse effects in environmental impact assessments; information disclosure requirements; and voluntary compliance of firms with international regulating norms. Prerequisites: MATH 51. Recommended: 70.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103499,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Ortolano, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Ortolano, L."],"location":"50-52H"}],"id":31864}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"172A":{"department":"CEE","number":"172A","title":"Indoor Air Quality (CEE 278C)","description":"Factors affecting the levels of air pollutants in the built indoor environment. The influence of ventilation, office equipment, floor coverings, furnishings, cleaning practices, and human activities on air quality including carbon dioxide, VOCs, resuspended dust, and airborne molds and fungi. Limited enrollment, preference to CEE students.  Prerequisites: Math 42 or 21 and CEE 70, or equivalents.","min_units":2,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":205295,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":27281}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"174A":{"department":"CEE","number":"174A","title":"Providing Safe Water for the Developing and Developed World","description":"This course will cover basic hydraulics and the fundamental processes used to provide and control water, and will introduce the basics of engineering design. In addition to understanding the details behind the fundamental processes, students will learn to feel comfortable developing initial design criteria (30% designs) for fundamental processes. Students should also develop a feel for the typical values of water treatment parameters and the equipment involved. The course should enable students to work competently in environmental engineering firms or on non-profit projects in the developing world such as Engineers without Borders. Pre-requisite: Chem31B/X.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214994,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Mitch, W."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Mitch, W."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":16468}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"174B":{"department":"CEE","number":"174B","title":"Wastewater Treatment: From Disposal to Resource Recovery","description":"This course builds upon CEE 174A, covering basic hydraulics and the fundamental processes used to treat wastewater. In addition to understanding the details behind the fundamental processes, students will learn to feel comfortable developing initial design criteria (30% designs) for fundamental processes. Students should also develop a feel for the typical values of water treatment parameters and the equipment involved. After covering conventional processes, the class addresses newer processes used to meet emerging treatment objectives, including nutrient removal, composting of biosolids and recycling of wastewater for beneficial uses, including potable reuse. Pre-requisites: CEE 174A.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214995,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Mitch, W."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Mitch, W."],"location":"Gates B12"}],"id":33464}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"176A":{"department":"CEE","number":"176A","title":"Energy Efficient Buildings","description":"Analysis and design. Thermal analysis of building envelope, heating and cooling requirements, HVAC, and building integrated PV systems. Emphasis is on residential passive solar design and solar water heating. Lab.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103506,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Masters, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Masters, G."],"location":""}],"id":28109}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"176C":{"department":"CEE","number":"176C","title":"Energy Storage Integration - Vehicles, Renewables, and the Grid (CEE 276C)","description":"This course will provide in-depth introduction to existing energy storage solutions being used on the electric grid and in vehicles with a primary focus on batteries and electrochemical storage.  We will discuss the operating characteristics, cost and efficiency of these technologies and how tradeoff decisions can be made.  Special attention will be given to system-level integration of new storage technologies, including chargers, inverters, battery management systems and controls, into the existing vehicle and grid infrastructure. Further investigations include issues relating to integration of electric vehicle charging with demand-side management, scheduled renewable energy absorption and local grid balancing. Class format involves regular guest lectures, required lab participation, and field trips to relevant sites. Enrollment is limited; if you are interested in taking the course, please fill out a brief questionnaire at http://goo.gl/forms/i3YH91Qx05  n Please contact jtaggart@stanford.edu with any questions regarding the application or course information.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214683,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Straubel, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Straubel, J."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":29248}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"177":{"department":"CEE","number":"177","title":"Aquatic Chemistry and Biology","description":"Introduction to chemical and biological processes in the aqueous environment. Basic aqueous equilibria; the structure, behavior, and fate of major classes of chemicals that dissolve in water; redox reactions; the biochemistry of aquatic microbial life; and biogeochemical processes that govern the fate of nutrients and metals in the environment and in engineered systems. Prerequisite: CHEM 31.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103508,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Criddle, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Criddle, C."],"location":"Hewlett Teaching Center 103"}],"id":16157}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"179A":{"department":"CEE","number":"179A","title":"Water Chemistry Laboratory (CEE 273A)","description":"(Graduate students register for 273A.) Laboratory application of techniques for the analysis of natural and contaminated waters, emphasizing instrumental techniques.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103512,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Leckie, J."],"location":""}],"id":46343},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Leckie, J."],"location":""}],"id":16002}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"180":{"department":"CEE","number":"180","title":"Structural Analysis","description":"Analysis of beams, trusses, frames; method of indeterminate analysis by consistent displacement, least work, superposition equations, moment distribution. Introduction to matrix methods and computer methods of structural analysis. Prerequisite: 101A and ENGR 14.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103513,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kiremidjian, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Kiremidjian, A."],"location":"Littlefield 107"}],"id":16158}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"181":{"department":"CEE","number":"181","title":"Design of Steel Structures","description":"Concepts of the design of steel structures with a load and resistance factor design (LRFD) approach; types of loading; structural systems; design of tension members, compression members, beams, beam-columns, and connections; and design of trusses and frames. Prerequisite: 180.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103516,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Law, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Law, K."],"location":"540-108"}],"id":16160}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"182":{"department":"CEE","number":"182","title":"Design of Reinforced Concrete Structures","description":"Properties of concrete and reinforcing steel; behavior of structural elements subject to bending moments, shear forces, torsion, axial loads, and combined actions; design of beams, slabs, columns and footings; strength design and serviceability requirements; design of simple structural systems for buildings. Prerequisite: 180.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103517,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Lepech, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Lepech, M."],"location":"Ceras 300"}],"id":28155}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"195":{"department":"CEE","number":"195","title":"Fundamentals of Structural Geology (GS 111)","description":"Techniques for mapping using GPS and differential geometry to characterize structures; dimensional analysis and scaling relations; kinematics of deformation and flow; measurement and analysis of stress; elastic deformation and properties of rock; brittle deformation including fracture and faulting; linear viscous flow including folding and magma dynamics; model development and methodology. Models of tectonic processes are constructed and solutions visualized using MATLAB. Prerequisites: GES 1, MATH 51","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-FR", "WAY-SMA"],"id":211998,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pollard, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pollard, D."],"location":"320-107"}],"id":32937}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"1A":{"department":"CEE","number":"1A","title":"Graphics Course","description":"This course, intended for students taking a design studio, will focus on presentation theories, skills and design approaches.  Through readings and exercises, and ultimately the student's own work, students will develop skill and complexity in their graphic and verbal presentations","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":216288,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Choe, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G.","Choe, B."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":17403}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wood, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Wood, E."],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":15844}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"201D":{"department":"CEE","number":"201D","title":"Computations in Civil and Environmental Engineering (CEE 101D)","description":"Computational and visualization methods in the design and analysis of civil and environmental engineering systems. Focus is on applications of MATLAB. How to develop a more lucid and better organized programming style.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103453,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15313}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"203":{"department":"CEE","number":"203","title":"Probabilistic Models in Civil Engineering","description":"Introduction to probability modeling and statistical analysis in civil engineering. Emphasis is on the practical issues of model selection, interpretation, and calibration. Application of common probability models used in civil engineering including Poisson processes and extreme value distributions. Parameter estimation. Linear regression.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103535,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Gupta, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Gupta, A."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":16161}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"206":{"department":"CEE","number":"206","title":"Decision Analysis for  Civil and Environmental Engineers","description":"Current challenges in selecting an appropriate site, alternate design, or retrofit strategy based on environmental, economic, and social factors can be best addressed through applications of decision science. Basics of decision theory, including development of decision trees with discrete and continuous random variables, expected value decision making, utility theory value of information, and elementary multi-attribute decision making will be covered in the class. Examples will cover many areas of civil and environmental engineering problems. Prerequisite: CEE 203 or equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":208210,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kiremidjian, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kiremidjian, A."],"location":""}],"id":45872}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"207A":{"department":"CEE","number":"207A","title":"Understanding Energy (CEE 107A, EARTHSYS 103)","description":"Energy is one of the world's main drivers of opportunity and development for human beings. At the same time, our energy system has significant consequences for our society, political system, economy, and environment. For example, energy production and use is the #1 source of greenhouse gas emissions. This course surveys key aspects of each energy resource, including significance and potential conversion processes and technologies, drivers and barriers, policy and regulatory environment, and social, economic, and environmental impacts. Both depletable and renewable energy resources are covered, including oil, natural gas, coal, nuclear, biomass, hydroelectric, wind, solar, photovoltaics, geothermal, and ocean energy, with cross-cutting topics including electricity, storage, climate change, sustainability, green buildings, energy efficiency, transportation, and the developing world. Understanding Energy is part of a trio of inter-related courses aimed at gaining an in-depth understanding of each energy resource - from fossil fuels to renewable energy. The other two classes are CEE107W/207W Understanding Energy - Workshop, and CEE 107F/207F Understanding Energy -- Field Trips.  Note that this course was formerly called Energy Resources (CEE 173A/207A & Earthsys 103). Prerequisites: Algebra. May not be taken for credit by students who have completed CEE 107S.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":129085,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Grubert, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Ginnebaugh, D.","Knapp, K.","Woodward, J.","Grubert, E."],"location":"Cubberley Auditorium"}],"id":15996}],[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"207F":{"department":"CEE","number":"207F","title":"Understanding Energy -- Field Trips (CEE 107F)","description":"Understanding Energy -- Field Trips takes students on trips to some of the most significant energy resource sites in North American located within a few hours of Stanford University. Students visit at least two of the many field trips offered, including to Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant, an Altmont Pass wind farm, a geothermal facility at The Geysers, a solar photovoltaic (PV) farm, Shasta Dam and hydroelectric power plant, a major oil field, and a natural gas-fired power plant, an energy efficiency technology lab, among others. Students meet on a weekly basis to debrief previous field trips and prepare for future ones. Open to all majors and backgrounds. Understanding Energy Field Trips is part of a trio of inter-related courses aimed at gaining an in-depth understanding of each energy resource -- from fossil fuels to renewable energy. The other two classes are CEE 107A/207A Understanding Energy, and CEE 107W/207W Understanding Energy - Workshop. Priority is given to students who have taken or are concurrently enrolled in CEE 173A, CEE 107A, CEE 207A, Earthsys 103, or CEE 107S/207S.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217151,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Knapp, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Knapp, K."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":29033}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Activity"},
"209":{"department":"CEE","number":"209","title":"Risk Quantification and Insurance","description":"Principles of risk management along with concepts of frequency and severity and various risk measures such as probabilities of exceeding given loss level, probabilities of insolvency, and expected value of shortfall will be introduced. Various risk handlingn techniques will be discussed with particular emphasis on insurance. Ability to express preferences between random future gains or losses, will be presented in the context of stochastic ordering of risks. Credibility theory and generalized linear models will be used for claims predictions.  Prerequisites: CEE 203 or equivalent.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":215925,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Singhal, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Singhal, A."],"location":"540-108"}],"id":33794}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"212A":{"department":"CEE","number":"212A","title":"Industry Applications of Virtual Design & Construction","description":"Building upon the concept of the VDC Scorecard, CEE 112A/212A investigates in the management of Virtual Design and Construction (VDC) programs and projects in the building industry. Interacting with experts and professionals in real estate, architecture, engineering , construction and technology providers, students will learn from the industry applications of Building Information Modeling and its relationship with Integrated Project Delivery, Sustainable Design and Construction, and Virtual Design and Construction. Students will conduct case studies to evaluate the maturity of VDC planning, adoption, technology and performance in practice. Students taking 3 or 4 units will be paired up with independent research or case study projects on the industry applications of VDC. No prerequisite. See CEE 112B/212B in the Winter Quarter and CEE 112C/212C in the Spring Quarter.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":212508,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kam, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"7:30:00 PM","end":"9:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kam, C."],"location":""}],"id":34060}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"220A":{"department":"CEE","number":"220A","title":"Building Information Modeling Workshop (CEE 120A)","description":"The foundational Building Information Modeling course introduces techniques for creating, managing, and applying of building information models in the building design and construction process. The course covers processes and tools for creating, organizing, and working with 2D and 3D computer representations of building components and geometries to produce models used in architectural design, construction planning and documentation, rendering and visualization, simulation and analysis.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215127,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15742}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"220B":{"department":"CEE","number":"220B","title":"Building Information Modeling Workshop (CEE 120B)","description":"This course builds upon the Building Information Model concepts introduced in 120A/220A and illustrates how BIM modeling tools are used to design, analyze, and model building systems including structural, mechanical, electrical, plumbing and fire protection. Course covers the physical principles, design criteria, and design strategies for each system and explores processes and tools for modeling those systems and analyzing their performance.nTopics include: building envelopes, access systems, structural systems modeling and analysis, mechanical / HVAC systems, plumbing and fire protection systems, electrical systems, and systems integration/coordination.","min_units":2,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215128,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":30417}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Katz, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Katz, G."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":15938}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"9:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":0}]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"222A":{"department":"CEE","number":"222A","title":"Computer Integrated Architecture/Engineering/Construction (AEC) Global Teamwork","description":"AEC students engage in a crossdisciplinary, collaborative, geographically distributed, and multicultural project-based teamwork. AEC teams exercise their domain knowledge and information technologies in a multidisciplinary context focusing on the design and construction concept development phase of a comprehensive building project. Prerequisite: interview with Instructor in Autumn Quarter.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":208522,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"location":""}],"id":32326},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fruchter, R."],"location":""}],"id":46365}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"224X":{"department":"CEE","number":"224X","title":"Global Urban Development Program","description":"A year-long Project-Based Learning course on sustainable urban systems, in collaboration with Sechuan University, Chengdu, China. Students will form multidisciplinary teams of 8-10 and be assigned to study one of two cities: Chengdu, CN and San Jose, CA.  Teams will work closely with city partners including municipal officials, industry leaders, community groups, and local academics. First phase conducing research using geospatial data analysis of key performance indicators, second and third phases to address target goals identified in phase one. Teams will propose innovative plans, policies and/or programs for urban development to meet goals. Three quarter commitment preferred, two quarter commitment required. Enrollment limited to ten Stanford students by application. Preference to CEE graduate students within CEE (SDC) and from other departments, upperclass undergraduate applications accepted.","min_units":2,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":217230,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Leckie, J.","Ouyang, D."],"location":"Y2E2 184"}],"id":28863}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"225":{"department":"CEE","number":"225","title":"Defining Smart Cities: Visions of Urbanism for the 21st Century (CEE 125, URBANST 174)","description":"In a rapidly urbanizing world, \"the city\" paves the way toward sustainability and social well-being. But what does it mean for a city to be smart? Does that also make it sustainable or resilient or livable? This seminar delves into current debates about urbanism through weekly talks by experts on topics such as big data, human-centered design, new urbanism, and natural capital. How urban spaces are shaped, for better or worse, by the complex interaction of cutting-edge technology, human societies, and the natural environment. The goal is to provoke vigorous discussion and to foster an understanding of cities that is at once technological, humanistic, and ecologically sound.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":216985,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hsu, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Law, K.","Hsu, K.","Chan, D."],"location":"160-124"}],"id":28738}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"226":{"department":"CEE","number":"226","title":"Life Cycle Assessment for Complex Systems","description":"Life cycle modeling of products, industrial processes, and infrastructure/building systems; material and energy balances for large interdependent systems; environmental accounting; and life cycle costing. These methods, based on ISO 14000 standards, are used to examine emerging technologies, such as biobased products, building materials, building integrated photovoltaics, and alternative design strategies, such as remanufacturing, dematerialization, LEED, and Design for Environment: DfE. Student teams complete a life cycle assessment of a product or system chosen from industry.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":208391,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Lepech, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Lepech, M."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":16107}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"234B":{"department":"CEE","number":"234B","title":"Intermediate Arch Studio (CEE 134B)","description":"This studio offers students experience in working with a real site and a real client program to develop a community facility. Students will develop site analysis, review a program for development and ultimately design their own solutions that meet client and community goals. Sustainability, historic preservation, community needs and materials will all play a part in the development of students final project. Students will also gain an understanding of graphic conventions, verbal and presentation techniques. Course may be repeated for credit.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"id":208667,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Shiles, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Barton, J.","Shiles, B."],"location":""}],"id":15672}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"6:00:00 PM","end":"8:50:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":15443}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"241":{"department":"CEE","number":"241","title":"Managing Fabrication and Construction","description":"Methods to manage the physical production of construction projects; design, analysis, and optimization of the fabricate-assemble process including performance metrics. Project management techniques and production system design including: push versus pull methods; master scheduling and look-ahead scheduling; scope, cost, and schedule control; earned value analysis; critical path method; location-based scheduling; 4D modeling; workflow; trade coordination; methods to understand uncertainty and reduce process variability; and supply chain systems including made-to-stock, engineered-to-order, and made-to-order. Prerequisite: 100 or consent of instructor. Recommended corequisite: 240.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103600,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fischer, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Fischer, M."],"location":"Thornt110"}],"id":16163}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"241A":{"department":"CEE","number":"241A","title":"Infrastructure Project Development (CEE 141A)","description":"Infrastructure is critical to the economy, global competitiveness and quality of life. Topics include energy, transportation, water, public facilities, and communications sectors. Analysis of the condition of the nation's infrastructure and how projects are planned and financed. Focus is on public works in the U.S. The role of public and private sectors through a step-by-step study of the project development process. Case studies of real infrastructure projects. Industry guest speakers. Student teams prepare project environmental impact statements.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":210192,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":"380-380X"}],"id":15710}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"241P":{"department":"CEE","number":"241P","title":"Integrated  Management of Fabrication and Construction","description":"Application of the fundamental fabrication and construction management concepts covered in CEE 241T to an actual project; integrated software environments; integration of scope, schedule, and cost information for scheduling, estimating, and progress control; scope management with BIM; off-site fabrication vs. on-site construction and supply chain coordination; group project; project permitting, potential for a joint project with CEE 242P. Prerequisites: CEE 210, CEE 241T.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":215178,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":45992}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"242":{"department":"CEE","number":"242","title":"Organization Design for Projects and Companies","description":"Introduction to organizational behavior and organizational design for construction projects and companies. Class incorporates readings, individual, small group and large group case study assignments. Students use computer simulation to design real-world project organizations.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103601,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Levitt, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Levitt, R."],"location":""}],"id":45722}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"244":{"department":"CEE","number":"244","title":"Accounting, Finance & Valuation for Engineers & Constructors","description":"Concepts of financial accounting and economics emphasizing the construction industry. Financial statements, accounting concepts, project accounting methods, and the nature of project costs. Case study of major construction contractor. Ownership structure, working capital, and the sources and uses of funds.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":103604,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Tucker, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"6:30:00 PM","end":"8:20:00 PM","instructors":["Tucker, A.","Meyer, P."],"location":"Thornt110"}],"id":16165}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"249":{"department":"CEE","number":"249","title":"Labor and Industrial Relations: Negotiations, Strikes, and Dispute Resolution","description":"Labor/management negotiations, content of a labor agreement, strikes, dispute resolution, contemporary issues affecting labor and management, and union versus open shop competitiveness in the marketplace. Case studies; presentations by union leaders, legal experts, and contractor principals. Simulated negotiation session with union officials and role play in an arbitration hearing.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":103614,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Walton, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Walton, M."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":28135}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"252P":{"department":"CEE","number":"252P","title":"Construction Engineering Practicum","description":"Construction engineering is a series of technical activities to meet project objectives related to cost and schedule, safety, quality, and sustainability. These activities include: 1) designing temporary works and construction work processes; 2) providing the required temporary and permanent resources; and 3) integrating activities to consider construction during all project phases and between projects. The objectives of CEE252P are to learn about the technical fundamentals, resources, and field operations required to complete construction engineering activities and to develop a foundation for continued related learning. The course requires reviewing recorded presentations and other online resources, completing queries, participating in class sessions with guest speakers and in field trips, completing group exercises and projects, and preparing an individual final paper. The exercises, completed by all groups, include construction engineering activities for earthwork, concrete construction, and steel erection. Each group will also complete a project to analyze one of the following types of systems or facilities: building electrical systems, lighting systems, HVAC systems, control systems, solar photovoltaic power plant, solar thermal power plant, and wind turbine power plant.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":211180,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Lepech, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Levitt, R.","Lepech, M."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"},{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Lepech, M.","Levitt, R."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":17186}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Practicum"},
"256":{"department":"CEE","number":"256","title":"Building Systems (CEE 156)","description":"HVAC, lighting, and envelope systems for commercial and institutional buildings, with a focus on energy efficient design. Knowledge and skills required in the development of low-energy buildings that provide high quality environment for occupants.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103488,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kolderup, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kolderup, E."],"location":"300-300"}],"id":33292}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"258":{"department":"CEE","number":"258","title":"Donald R. Watson Seminar in Construction Engineering and Management","description":"Presentations from construction industry leaders. Discussions with speakers from various segments of industry regarding career options. Student groups interact with industry representatives after class.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":103625,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Griggs, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Griggs, G."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":15900}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"260A":{"department":"CEE","number":"260A","title":"Physical Hydrogeology (ESS 220)","description":"(Formerly GES 230.) Theory of underground water occurrence and flow, analysis of field data and aquifer tests, geologic groundwater environments, solution of field problems,  and groundwater modeling. Introduction to groundwater contaminant transport and unsaturated flow. Lab. Prerequisite: elementary calculus.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":129537,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Gorelick, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Gorelick, S."],"location":"320-220"}],"id":16008}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"260C":{"department":"CEE","number":"260C","title":"Contaminant Hydrogeology and Reactive Transport (ESS 221, GS 225)","description":"For earth scientists and engineers. Environmental, geologic, and water resource problems involving migration of contaminated groundwater through porous media and associated biogeochemical and fluid-rock reactions. Conceptual and quantitative treatment of advective-dispersive transport with reacting solutes. Predictive models of contaminant behavior controlled by local equilibrium and kinetics. Modern methods of contaminant transport simulation and reactive transport modeling using geochemical transport software.  Some Matlab programming / program modification required. Prerequisite: Physical Hydrogeology EESS 220 / CEE 260A (Gorelick) or equivalent. Recommended: course work in environmental chemistry or geochemistry (e.g., one or more of the following: EESS 155, EESS 156/256 GES 90, GES 170/279, GES 171, CEE 177 or CEE 270).","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":129538,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Gorelick, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Maher, K.","Gorelick, S."],"location":""}],"id":32938}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"261":{"department":"CEE","number":"261","title":"Physics of Wind Energy (ME 262)","description":"An introduction to the analysis and modeling of wind energy resources and their extraction.  Topics include the physical origins of atmospheric winds; vertical profiles of wind speed and turbulence over land and sea; the wind energy spectrum and its modification by natural topography and built environments; theoretical limits on wind energy extraction by wind turbines and wind farms; modeling of wind turbine aerodynamics and wind farm performance. Final project will focus on development of a new wind energy technology concept.  Prerequisites: CEE 262A or ME 351A","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":217073,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Dabiri, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"9:00:00 AM","end":"10:00:00 AM","instructors":["Dabiri, J."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":46563}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"262A":{"department":"CEE","number":"262A","title":"Hydrodynamics","description":"The flow of incompressible viscous fluid; emphasis is on developing an understanding of fluid dynamics that can be applied to environmental flows. Topics: kinematics of fluid flow; equations of mass and momentum conservation (including density variations); some exact solutions to the Navier-Stokes equations; appropriate analysis of fluid flows including Stokes flows, potential flows, and laminar boundary layers; and an introduction to the effects of rotation and stratification through scaling analysis of fluid flows. Prerequisites: 101B or consent of instructor; and some knowledge of vector calculus and differential equations.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103642,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":16167}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"262C":{"department":"CEE","number":"262C","title":"Modeling Environmental Flows","description":"Introduction to numerical methods for modeling surface water flows in rivers, lakes, estuaries and the coastal ocean. Topics include stability and accuracy analysis, curvilinear and unstructured grids, implicit/explicit methods, transport and diffusion, shallow water equations, nonhydrostatic equations, Navier-Stokes solvers, turbulence modeling. Prerequisites: CEE262A, CME206, or equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":204560,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fringer, O."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fringer, O."],"location":"Y2E2 105"}],"id":45852}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"262D":{"department":"CEE","number":"262D","title":"Introduction to Physical Oceanography (CEE 164, EARTHSYS 164, ESS 148)","description":"The dynamic basis of oceanography. Topics: physical environment; conservation equations for salt, heat, and momentum; geostrophic flows; wind-driven flows; the Gulf Stream; equatorial dynamics and ENSO; thermohaline circulation of the deep oceans; and tides. Prerequisite: PHYSICS 41 (formerly 53).","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":129098,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fong, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fong, D."],"location":""}],"id":32541}],[]],"primary_type":"Discussion"},
"263C":{"department":"CEE","number":"263C","title":"Weather and Storms (CEE 63)","description":"Daily and severe weather and global climate. Topics: structure and composition of the atmosphere, fog and cloud formation, rainfall, local winds, wind energy, global circulation, jet streams, high and low pressure systems, inversions, el Ni&ntilde;o, la Ni&ntilde;a, atmosphere/ocean interactions, fronts, cyclones, thunderstorms, lightning, tornadoes, hurricanes, pollutant transport, global climate and atmospheric optics.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103438,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":15304}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"263D":{"department":"CEE","number":"263D","title":"Air Pollution and Global Warming: History, Science, and Solutions (CEE 64)","description":"Survey of Survey of air pollution and global warming and their renewable energy solutions. Topics: evolution of the Earth's atmosphere, history of discovery of chemicals in the air, bases and particles in urban smog, visibility, indoor air pollution, acid rain, stratospheric and Antarctic ozone loss, the historic climate record, causes and effects of global warming, impacts of energy systems on pollution and climate, renewable energy solutions to air pollution and global warming. UG Reqs: GER: DBNatSci","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103440,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Turingaud"}],"id":16000}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"263E":{"department":"CEE","number":"263E","title":"International Climate Negotiations: Unpacking the Road to Paris (CEE 163E, EARTHSYS 163E, EARTHSYS 263E)","description":"Interested in what's going on with international climate negotiations, why it has proven so difficult to reach a meaningful agreement? Wondering whether or not another UN agreement is even a meaningful part of climate policy in 2015? This course traces the history of climate negotiations from the very first awareness of the problem of climate change, through the Kyoto Protocol and Copenhagen Accord, to the current state of international negotiations in the lead-up to the 21st Conference of the Parties meeting in Paris in December 2015. The course covers fundamental concepts in climate change science and policy, international law and multilateral environmental agreements, as well as key issues of climate finance, climate justice, equity, adaptation, communication, and social movements that together comprise the subjects of debate in the negotiations. We will discuss all the key facets of what&iquest;s being negotiated in Paris and prepare students to follow the outcome of the negotiation in detail. Students also participate in a three-day mock conference of the parties. By application only.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216942,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nevle, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Nevle, R.","Tangri, N.","Strong, A."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":28719}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"263F":{"department":"CEE","number":"263F","title":"Groundwork for COP21 (CEE 163F, EARTHSYS 163F, EARTHSYS 263F)","description":"This course will prepare undergraduate and coterm students to participate in the climate change negotiations (COP 21) in Paris in November/December 2015. Students will develop individual projects to be carried out before and during the negotiation session and be paired with graduate student mentors. Please note: Along with EARTHSYS 163E/CEE 163E, this course is part of the required two-course-set in which undergraduate and co-terminal masters degree students must enroll to receive accreditation to the climate negotiations.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217077,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Nevle, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"6:00:00 PM","end":"7:20:00 PM","instructors":["Cina, S.","Nevle, R.","Tangri, N.","Strong, A."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":29037}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"263S":{"department":"CEE","number":"263S","title":"Atmosphere/Energy Seminar","description":"Interdisciplinary seminar with talks by researchers and practitioners in the fields of atmospheric science and renewable energy engineering. Addresses the causes of climate, air pollution, and weather problems and methods of addressing these problems through renewable and efficient energy systems. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":214285,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Hewlett Teaching Center 102"}],"id":17173}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Y2E2 299"}],"id":15701}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"266A":{"department":"CEE","number":"266A","title":"Watersheds and Wetlands (CEE 166A)","description":"Introduction to the occurrence and movement of water in the natural environment and its role in creating and maintaining terrestrial, wetland, and aquatic habitat. Hydrologic processes, including precipitation, evaporation, transpiration, snowmelt, infiltration, subsurface flow, runoff, and streamflow. Rivers and lakes, springs and swamps. Emphasis is on observation and measurement, data analysis, modeling, and prediction. Prerequisite: 101B or equivalent. (Freyberg)","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":202123,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["MacVean, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["MacVean, L."],"location":"200-305"}],"id":15333}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"266B":{"department":"CEE","number":"266B","title":"Floods and Droughts, Dams and Aqueducts (CEE 166B)","description":"Sociotechnical systems associated with human use of water as a resource and the hazards posed by too much or too little water. Potable and non-potable water use and conservation. Irrigation, hydroelectric power generation, rural and urban water supply systems, storm water management, flood damage mitigation, and water law and institutions. Emphasis is on engineering design. Prerequisite: 166A or equivalent. (Freyberg)","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":202124,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":""}],"id":28096}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"268":{"department":"CEE","number":"268","title":"Groundwater Flow","description":"Flow and mass transport in porous media. Applications of potential flow theory and numerical modeling methods to practical groundwater problems: flow to and from wells, rivers, lakes, drainage ditches; flow through and under dams; streamline tracing; capture zones of wells; and mixing schemes for in-situ remediation. Prerequisites: calculus and introductory fluid mechanics.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103663,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"location":"Y2E2 105"}],"id":45723}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"269A":{"department":"CEE","number":"269A","title":"Environmental Fluid Mechanics and Hydrology Seminar","description":"Problems in all branches of water resources. Talks by visitors, faculty, and students. May be repeated two times for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":212871,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":[],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":17084}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"269B":{"department":"CEE","number":"269B","title":"Environmental Fluid Mechanics and Hydrology Seminar","description":"Problems in all branches of water resources. Talks by visitors, faculty, and students. May be repeated two times for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":212872,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fringer, O."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fringer, O."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":33170}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"270":{"department":"CEE","number":"270","title":"Movement and Fate of Organic Contaminants in  Waters","description":"Transport of chemical constituents in surface and groundwater including advection, dispersion, sorption, interphase mass transfer, and transformation; impacts on water quality. Emphasis is on physicochemical processes and the behavior of hazardous waste contaminants. Prerequisites: undergraduate chemistry and calculus. Recommended: 101B.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103666,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Luthy, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"9:20:00 AM","instructors":["Luthy, R."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":16170}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"271A":{"department":"CEE","number":"271A","title":"Physical and Chemical Treatment Processes","description":"Physical and chemical unit operations for water treatment, emphasizing process combinations for drinking water supply. Application of the principles of chemistry, rate processes, fluid dynamics, and process engineering to define and solve water treatment problems by flocculation, sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, oxidation, aeration, and adsorption. Investigative paper on water supply and treatment. Prerequisites: 101B, 270. Recommended: 273.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103668,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Choi, Y."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"9:20:00 AM","instructors":["Choi, Y.","Luthy, R."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":28037}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"271B":{"department":"CEE","number":"271B","title":"Environmental Biotechnology","description":"Stoichiometry, kinetics, and thermodynamics of microbial processes for the transformation of environmental contaminants. Design of dispersed growth and biofilm-based processes. Applications include treatment of municipal and industrial waste waters, detoxification of hazardous chemicals, and groundwater remediation. Prerequisites: 270; 177 or 274A or equivalents.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103669,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Strong, N."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Criddle, C.","Strong, N."],"location":""}],"id":28038}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"272":{"department":"CEE","number":"272","title":"Coastal Contaminants","description":"Coastal pollution and its effects on ecosystems and human health. The sources, fate, and transport of human pathogens and nutrients. Background on coastal ecosystems and coastal transport phenomena including tides, waves, and cross shelf transport. Introduction to time series analysis with MATLAB. Undergraduates require consent of instructor.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103672,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Boehm, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Boehm, A."],"location":"McCullough 122"}],"id":16172}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"273":{"department":"CEE","number":"273","title":"Aquatic Chemistry","description":"Chemical principles and their application to the analysis and solution of problems in aqueous geochemistry (temperatures near 25&deg; C and atmospheric pressure). Emphasis is on natural water systems and the solution of specific chemical problems in water purification technology and water pollution control. Prerequisites: CHEM 31 and 33, or equivalents.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":129569,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Leckie, J."],"location":"Turingaud"}],"id":15244}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture","secondary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Leckie, J."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":28968}],[],[]],"secondary_type":"Discussion"},
"273A":{"department":"CEE","number":"273A","title":"Water Chemistry Laboratory (CEE 179A)","description":"(Graduate students register for 273A.) Laboratory application of techniques for the analysis of natural and contaminated waters, emphasizing instrumental techniques.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103512,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Leckie, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Leckie, J."],"location":""}],"id":16003}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"274A":{"department":"CEE","number":"274A","title":"Environmental Microbiology I (CHEMENG 174, CHEMENG 274)","description":"Basics of microbiology and biochemistry. The biochemical and biophysical principles of biochemical reactions, energetics, and mechanisms of energy conservation. Diversity of microbial catabolism, flow of organic matter in nature: the carbon cycle, and biogeochemical cycles. Bacterial physiology, phylogeny, and the ecology of microbes in soil and marine sediments, bacterial adhesion, and biofilm formation. Microbes in the degradation of pollutants. Prerequisites: CHEM 33, 35, and BIOSCI 41, CHEMENG 181 (formerly 188), or equivalents.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103678,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Spormann, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Spormann, A."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":15318}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"274B":{"department":"CEE","number":"274B","title":"Microbial Bioenergy Systems (CHEMENG 456)","description":"Introduction to microbial metabolic pathways and to the pathway logic with a special focus on microbial bioenergy systems.  The first part of the course emphasizes the metabolic and biochemical principles of pathways, whereas the second part is more specifically directed toward using this knowledge to understand existing systems and to design innovative microbial bioenergy systems for biofuel, biorefinery, and environmental applications. There also is an emphasis on the implications of rerouting of energy and reducing equivalents for the fitness and ecology of the organism. Prerequisites: CHEMENG 174 or 181 and organic chemistry, or equivalents.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103679,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Spormann, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Spormann, A."],"location":"Y2E2 335"}],"id":16006}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"275K":{"department":"CEE","number":"275K","title":"The Practice of Environmental Consulting","description":"Class consists of eight interactive two-hour seminars with discussions, and will cover the evolution of the environmental consulting business, strategic choices and alternative business models for private and public firms, a review of the key operational issues in managing firm, organizational strategies, knowledge management and innovation, and ethical issues in providing professional services. Case studies will be used to illustrate key concepts. Selected reading materials drawn from the technical and business literature on the consulting business. Student groups will prepare and present an abbreviated business plan for an environmental based business. Enrollment limited to CEE MS and PHD students.","min_units":2,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"id":215077,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kavanaugh, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kavanaugh, M."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":46331},{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kavanaugh, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kavanaugh, M."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":45096}],[]],"primary_type":"Practicum"},
"276C":{"department":"CEE","number":"276C","title":"Energy Storage Integration - Vehicles, Renewables, and the Grid (CEE 176C)","description":"This course will provide in-depth introduction to existing energy storage solutions being used on the electric grid and in vehicles with a primary focus on batteries and electrochemical storage.  We will discuss the operating characteristics, cost and efficiency of these technologies and how tradeoff decisions can be made.  Special attention will be given to system-level integration of new storage technologies, including chargers, inverters, battery management systems and controls, into the existing vehicle and grid infrastructure. Further investigations include issues relating to integration of electric vehicle charging with demand-side management, scheduled renewable energy absorption and local grid balancing. Class format involves regular guest lectures, required lab participation, and field trips to relevant sites. Enrollment is limited; if you are interested in taking the course, please fill out a brief questionnaire at http://goo.gl/forms/i3YH91Qx05  n Please contact jtaggart@stanford.edu with any questions regarding the application or course information.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214683,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Straubel, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Straubel, J."],"location":"530-127"}],"id":29249}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"277C":{"department":"CEE","number":"277C","title":"Environmental Governance (ENVRES 250)","description":"This interdisciplinary course presents an overview of environmental governance through an examination of how and why societies manage the relationships between human beings and the natural world. By comparing regulatory, community-based, and incentive-based environmental management systems, we address why certain environmental problems are managed as they are, and what approaches to environmental management are more (or less) successful. Designed for graduate students and upper-level undergraduates with some exposure to both the natural sciences (ecology/environmental chemistry), and the social sciences (anthropology, economics, political science, or sociology). A pre-course incoming survey is required.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214957,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Strong, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"6:20:00 PM","instructors":["Strong, A."],"location":"Y2E2 335"}],"id":46550}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"278A":{"department":"CEE","number":"278A","title":"Air Pollution Fundamentals","description":"The sources and health effects of gaseous and particulate air pollutants. The influence of meteorology on pollution: temperature profiles, stability classes, inversion layers, turbulence. Atmospheric diffusion equations, downwind dispersion of emissions from point and line sources. Removal of air pollutants via settling, diffusion, coagulation, precipitation, Mechanisms for ozone formation, in the troposphere versus in the stratosphere. Effects of airborne particle size and composition on light scattering/absorption, and on visual range. Prerequisites: MATH 51 or equivalent. Recommended: 101B, CHEM 31A, or equivalents.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103691,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":45427}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"278C":{"department":"CEE","number":"278C","title":"Indoor Air Quality (CEE 172A)","description":"Factors affecting the levels of air pollutants in the built indoor environment. The influence of ventilation, office equipment, floor coverings, furnishings, cleaning practices, and human activities on air quality including carbon dioxide, VOCs, resuspended dust, and airborne molds and fungi. Limited enrollment, preference to CEE students.  Prerequisites: Math 42 or 21 and CEE 70, or equivalents.","min_units":2,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":205295,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":27282}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"279":{"department":"CEE","number":"279","title":"Environmental Engineering Seminar","description":"Current research, practice, and thinking in environmental engineering and science. Attendance at seminars is self-directed, the 20 hours of required seminar attendance may be accrued throughout the school year.  Must prepare a publication synopsis, and maintain log of seminar attendance.  See Aut Qtr CEE 279 syllabus for details on course requirements.  Contact hildemann@stanford.edu to be added to Coursework website.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":103694,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":15901}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Hildemann, L."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":15389}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"280":{"department":"CEE","number":"280","title":"Advanced Structural Analysis","description":"Theoretical development and computer implementation of direct stiffness method of structural analysis; virtual work principles; computation of element stiffness matrices and load vectors; direct assembly procedures; equation solution techniques. Analysis of two- and three-dimensional truss and frame structures, thermal loads, and substructuring and condensation techniques for large systems. Practical modeling techniques and programming assignments. Introduction to nonlinear analysis concepts. Prerequisites: elementary structural analysis and matrix algebra.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103697,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Deierlein, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Deierlein, G."],"location":"Thornt110"}],"id":16182}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"281":{"department":"CEE","number":"281","title":"Mechanics and Finite Elements","description":"Fluid conduction and solid deformation; conservation laws: balance of mass and balance of momentum; generalized Darcy's law and Hooke's law in 3D; the use of tensors in mechanics; finite element formulation of boundary-value problems; variational equations and Galerkin approximations; basic shape functions, numerical integration, and assembly operations.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103700,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Borja, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Borja, R."],"location":""}],"id":32722}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"282":{"department":"CEE","number":"282","title":"Nonlinear Structural Analysis","description":"Introduction to methods of geometric and material nonlinear analysis, emphasizing modeling approaches for framed structures. Large-displacement analysis, concentrated and distributed plasticity models, and nonlinear solution methods. Applications to frame stability and performance-based seismic design. Assignments emphasize computer implementation and applications. Prerequisites: 280 and an advanced course in structural behavior (e.g., 285A, 285B or equivalent).","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103704,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Deierlein, G."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"8:30:00 AM","end":"10:20:00 AM","instructors":["Deierlein, G."],"location":"540-108"}],"id":28864}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"283":{"department":"CEE","number":"283","title":"Structural Dynamics","description":"Vibrations and dynamic response of simple structures under time dependent loads; dynamic analysis of single and multiple degrees of freedom systems; support motion; response spectra.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":103707,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Law, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Law, K."],"location":""}],"id":32545}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"284":{"department":"CEE","number":"284","title":"Finite Element  Methods in Structural Dynamics","description":"Computational methods for structural dynamics analysis of discrete and continuous systems in free and forced vibration; finite element formulation; modal analysis; numerical methods; introduction to nonlinear dynamics; advanced topics. Prerequisites: 280, 283.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":200412,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Law, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"3:20:00 PM","instructors":["Law, K."],"location":"540-108"}],"id":28316}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"285A":{"department":"CEE","number":"285A","title":"Advanced Structural Concrete Behavior and Design","description":"Behavior and design of reinforced and prestressed concrete for building and bridge design.  Topics will include  flexural behavior, prestressed concrete design, and two-way slab design & analysis, among others.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":211215,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Billington, S."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Billington, S."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":16312}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"285B":{"department":"CEE","number":"285B","title":"Advanced Structural Steel Behavior and Design","description":"Advanced topics in structural steel design. Topics include composite floor systems; bolted and welded connections; beam-column connections; innovative lateral load resisting systems. As part of this course students design a 15-story steel building. Prerequisite: basic course in structural steel design CEE181 or equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":211216,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Miranda, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Miranda, E."],"location":"Thornt110"}],"id":33413}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"291":{"department":"CEE","number":"291","title":"Solid Mechanics","description":"Introduction to vectors and tensors; kinematics, deformation, forces, and stress concept of continua and structures; balance principles; aspects of objectivity; hyperelastic materials; thermodynamics of materials; variational principles; applications to structural engineering.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":214972,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Linder, C."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Linder, C."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":16467}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"293":{"department":"CEE","number":"293","title":"Foundations and Earth Structures","description":"Types, characteristics, analysis, and design of shallow and deep foundations; rigid and flexible retaining walls; braced excavations; settlement of footings in sands and clays; slope stability analysis by method of slices including search algorithms for the critical slip surface. Prerequisite: 101C or equivalent.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103718,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wren, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Wren, J."],"location":""}],"id":32803}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"297R":{"department":"CEE","number":"297R","title":"Structural Geology and Rock Mechanics (GEOPHYS 251, GS 215)","description":"Quantitative field and laboratory data integrated with solutions to boundary value problems of continuum mechanics to understand tectonic processes in Earth's crust that lead to the development of geological structures including folds, faults, fractures and fabrics. Topics include: techniques and tools for structural mapping&iquest; differential geometry to characterize structures&iquest; dimensional analysis and scaling relations&iquest; kinematics of deformation and flow&iquest; traction and stress analysis, conservation of mass and momentum in a deformable continuum&iquest; linear elastic deformation and elastic properties&iquest; brittle deformation including fracture and faulting&iquest; model development and methodology. Data sets analyzed using MATLAB. Prerequisites: GES 1, MATH 53, MATLAB or equivalent.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":211999,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Pollard, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"3:00:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Pollard, D."],"location":""}],"id":45049}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"298":{"department":"CEE","number":"298","title":"Structural Engineering and Geomechanics Seminar","description":"Recommended for all graduate students. Lectures on topics of current interest in professional practice and research.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":103726,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Baker, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:50:00 PM","instructors":["Baker, J."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":33257}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"301":{"department":"CEE","number":"301","title":"The Energy Seminar (ENERGY 301, MS&E 494)","description":"Interdisciplinary exploration of current energy challenges and opportunities, with talks by faculty, visitors, and students. May be repeated for credit.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":206975,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Weyant, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Weyant, J."],"location":""}],"id":15519}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Weyant, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"4:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Weyant, J."],"location":""}],"id":15538}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"31":{"department":"CEE","number":"31","title":"Accessing Architecture Through Drawing","description":"Preference to Architectural Design and CEE majors; others by consent of instructor. Drawing architecture to probe the intricacies and subtleties that characterize contemporary buildings. How to dissect buildings and appreciate the formal elements of a building, including scale, shape, proportion, colors and materials, and the problem solving reflected in the design. Students construct conventional architectural drawings, such as plans, elevations, and perspectives. Limited enrollment.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE", "GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":204579,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wood, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"9:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Wood, E."],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":28388}],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Wood, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Wood, E."],"location":"Y2E2 266"}],"id":46578}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"316":{"department":"CEE","number":"316","title":"Sustainable Built Environment Research","description":"Intended for early stage Ph.D. students in Sustainable Design and Construction (SDC). Covers dominant methodological approaches at the intersection of engineering, social management science and computer science. Overviews an array of methods available for research, focusing on methods commonly used in SDC. Publications using various methods will be analyzed, and journal review processes will be discussed. Major deliverable is research proposal using one or more of the methods discussed. Students will gain familiarity with the array of methods available for SDC research, know how to apply the methods in their own research area, and receive guidance on publishing their research in scientific journals.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":203774,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Eriksson, K."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Eriksson, K."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":45841}],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"31Q":{"department":"CEE","number":"31Q","title":"Accessing Architecture Through Drawing","description":"Preference to sophomores. Drawing architecture provides a deeper understanding of the intricacies and subtleties that characterize contemporary buildings. How to dissect buildings and appreciate the formal elements of a building, including scale, shape, proportion, colors and materials, and the problem solving reflected in the design. Students construct conventional architectural drawings, such as plans, elevations, and perspectives. Limited enrollment.","min_units":5,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-CE", "GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":202445,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Barton, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"2:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Barton, J."],"location":"420-245"}],"id":16059}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Introsem"},
"322":{"department":"CEE","number":"322","title":"Data Analytics for Urban Systems","description":"TBA","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216241,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Rajagopal, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Rajagopal, R."],"location":"Y2E2 292A"}],"id":16597}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"328A":{"department":"CEE","number":"328A","title":"Multidisciplinary Design and Simulation of Building Envelopes","description":"Curtain walls are a manufactured product ubiquitous in the world of architecture and engineering that must meet structural, thermal, acoustic, environmental, and economic performance requirements. This course focuses on design strategies for building envelopes and explores new design approaches including parametric 3D modeling, simulation, and Multidsiciplinary Design Optimization (MDO) methods that leverage computation to augment human abilities to identify novel, high performing solutions. Prerequisite: CEE 220A or equivalent. Limited to 16 students.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":216477,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Flager, F."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Flager, F."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 108"}],"id":34049}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"32A":{"department":"CEE","number":"32A","title":"Psychology of Architecture","description":"This course argues that architecture often neglects the interdisciplinary investigation of our internal psychological experience and the way it impacts our creation of space. How does our inner life influence external design? How are we impacted emotionally, physically, psychologically by the spaces we inhabit day to day? How might we intentionally imbue personal and public spaces with specific emotions? This seminar serves as a call to action for students interested in approaching architecture with a holistic understanding of the emotional impact of space. Sample topics addressed will include: conscious vs. unconscious design; the ego of architecture; psycho-spatial perspectives; ideas of home; integral/holistic architecture; phenomenology of inner and outer spaces; exploring archetypal architecture; and translating emotion through environment.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":212446,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Larimer, A."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"12:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Larimer, A."],"location":""}],"id":28509}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"32B":{"department":"CEE","number":"32B","title":"Design Theory","description":"This seminar focuses on the key themes, histories, and methods of architectural theory -- a form of architectural practice that establishes the aims and philosophies of architecture.  Architectural theory is primarily written, but it also incorporates drawing, photography, film, and other media.  nnOne of the distinctive features of modern and contemporary architecture is its pronounced use of theory to articulate its aims. One might argue that modern architecture is modern because of its incorporation of theory. This course focuses on those early-modern, modern, and late-modern writings that have been and remain entangled with contemporary architectural thought and design practice.  nnRather than examine the development of modern architectural theory chronologically, it is explored architectural through thematic topics. These themes enable the student to understand how certain architectural theoretical concepts endure, are transformed, and can be furthered through his/her own explorations.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-Hum"],"id":212627,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Beischer, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Beischer, T."],"location":"Y2E2 335"}],"id":45935}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"32R":{"department":"CEE","number":"32R","title":"American Architecture (AMSTUD 143A, ARTHIST 143A, ARTHIST 343A)","description":"A historically based understanding of what defines American architecture. What makes American architecture American, beginning with indigenous structures of pre-Columbian America. Materials, structure, and form in the changing American context. How these ideas are being transformed in today's globalized world.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":["GER:DB-Hum"],"id":206696,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Beischer, T."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:50:00 AM","instructors":["Beischer, T."],"location":"McCullough 122"}],"id":28411}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"32S":{"department":"CEE","number":"32S","title":"The Situated Workplace and Public Life","description":"The modern workplace has undergone fundamental change and continues to evolve. The context of work in many industries is today being shaped substantially by changing workforce demographics, the pervasiveness of mobile and embedded information technologies,  hyper-connected work models on a global scale, evolving notions of health and well being, etc. nnOur public realm is changing too. People are moving to cities in greater numbers than ever before posing both challenges and opportunities related to new levels of density, sustainable resource management, resilient infrastructures, as well as new forms of civic engagement at neighborhood levels, to name but a few. These changes at an urban scale impact how and where public life happens and how it interacts with new modalities at work.nnThis course will combine research, conceptual explorations, studio design work, seminars and guest lectures to explore the impact of the changing workplace on the morphology of the city by examining these bi-coastal seats of innovation. As the creative workplace continues to evolve, how will it engage the public realm within both well-established urban frameworks such as San Francisco and Boston, and emerging suburban contexts, such as Silicon Valley?nnThe course will join graduate students from the Northeastern University School of Architecture with students from the Stanford University Architectural Design program. Students will reside primarily at their prospective universities and will travel selectively for site research, team charettes and project reviews. Project sites on both coasts will be utilized for research and studio work. This is an opportunity for students from two top universities, both situated in the epicenters of workplace change, to explore and conduct valuable research on an  issue that is changing their urban environments.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":217179,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Shiles, B."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Shiles, B."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 052"}],"id":46204}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"362G":{"department":"CEE","number":"362G","title":"Stochastic Inverse Modeling and Data Assimilation Methods","description":"Stochastic methods for the solution of inverse problems that are algebraically underdetermined or have solutions that are sensitive to data. Emphasis is on geostatistical methods that, in addition to using data, incorporate information about structure such as spatial continuity and smoothness. Methods for real-time processing of new data. Prerequisite: consent of instructor.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":208423,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"3:30:00 PM","end":"5:20:00 PM","instructors":["Kitanidis, P."],"location":"Thornt110"}],"id":28441}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"363A":{"department":"CEE","number":"363A","title":"Mechanics of Stratified Flows","description":"The effects of density stratification on flows in the natural environment. Basic properties of linear internal waves in layered and continuous stratification. Flows established by internal waves. Internal hydraulics and gravity currents. Turbulence in stratified fluids. Prerequisites: 262A,B, CME 204.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":103753,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Fong, D."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"4:20:00 PM","instructors":["Fong, D."],"location":"Y2E2 101"}],"id":45724}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"379":{"department":"CEE","number":"379","title":"Introduction to PHD Studies in Civil and Environmental Engineering","description":"This seminar course will cover important topics for students considering a PhD in Civil and Environmental Engineering. Sessions will include presentations and discussions on career development, exploring research and adviser options, and the mechanics of PhD studies, including General Qualifying Exam requirements for all CEE PHD Students.  In addition, CEE faculty will give presentations on their research.  This seminar is required for CEE students considering a PHD or preparing to sit for the General Qualifying Exam in Civil and Environmental Engineering.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"id":217528,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Lepech, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"12:00:00 PM","end":"1:20:00 PM","instructors":["Lepech, M."],"location":"Y2E2 111"}],"id":30974}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Seminar"},
"385":{"department":"CEE","number":"385","title":"Performance-Based Earthquake Engineering","description":"Synthesis and application of approaches to performance-based design and assessment that recently have been developed or are under development. Emphasis is on quantitative decision making based on life-cycle considerations that incorporate direct losses, downtime losses, and collapse, and the associated uncertainties. Hazard analysis, response simulation, damage and loss estimation, collapse prediction. Case studies. Prerequisites: 282, 287, and 288.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"id":205984,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Miranda, E."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Miranda, E."],"location":"Gates B12"}],"id":16000}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"48N":{"department":"CEE","number":"48N","title":"Managing Complex, Global Projects","description":"This freshman seminar highlights the challenges the challenges associated with planning and executing complex and challenging global projects in private, governmental and nonprofit/NGO settings. Covers organization and project management theory, methods, and tools to optimize the design of work processes and organizations to enhance complex, global project outcomes. Student teams model and analyze the work process and organization of a real-world project team engaged in a challenging local or global project.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"id":206202,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Levitt, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Levitt, R."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 108"}],"id":45862}],[]],"primary_type":"Introsem"},
"63":{"department":"CEE","number":"63","title":"Weather and Storms (CEE 263C)","description":"Daily and severe weather and global climate. Topics: structure and composition of the atmosphere, fog and cloud formation, rainfall, local winds, wind energy, global circulation, jet streams, high and low pressure systems, inversions, el Ni&ntilde;o, la Ni&ntilde;a, atmosphere/ocean interactions, fronts, cyclones, thunderstorms, lightning, tornadoes, hurricanes, pollutant transport, global climate and atmospheric optics.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-SMA", "GER: DB-NatSci"],"id":103438,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"11:30:00 AM","end":"12:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Shriram Ctr BioChemE 104"}],"id":15302}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"64":{"department":"CEE","number":"64","title":"Air Pollution and Global Warming: History, Science, and Solutions (CEE 263D)","description":"Survey of Survey of air pollution and global warming and their renewable energy solutions. Topics: evolution of the Earth's atmosphere, history of discovery of chemicals in the air, bases and particles in urban smog, visibility, indoor air pollution, acid rain, stratospheric and Antarctic ozone loss, the historic climate record, causes and effects of global warming, impacts of energy systems on pollution and climate, renewable energy solutions to air pollution and global warming. UG Reqs: GER: DBNatSci","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-SMA", "GER: DB-NatSci"],"id":103440,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:20:00 PM","instructors":["Jacobson, M."],"location":"Turingaud"}],"id":15999}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"70":{"department":"CEE","number":"70","title":"Environmental Science and Technology (ENGR 90)","description":"Introduction to environmental quality and the technical background necessary for understanding environmental issues, controlling environmental degradation, and preserving air and water quality. Material balance concepts for tracking substances in the environmental and engineering systems.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-AQR", "GER:DB-EngrAppSci"],"id":103441,"primary":[[],[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Kopperud, R."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"10:30:00 AM","end":"11:20:00 AM","instructors":["Kopperud, R."],"location":"Cubberley Auditorium"}],"id":44883}],[]],"primary_type":"Lecture"},
"70N":{"department":"CEE","number":"70N","title":"Water, Public Health, and Engineering","description":"Preference to frosh. Linkages between water, wastewater and public health, with an emphasis on engineering interventions. Topics include the history of water and wastewater infrastructure development in the U.S. and Europe; evolution of epidemiological approaches for water-related health challenges; biological and chemical contaminants in water and wastewater and their management; and current trends and challenges in access to water and sanitation around the world. Identifying ways in which freshwater contributes to human health; exposure routes for water- and sanitation-illness. Classifying illnesses by pathogen type and their geographic distribution. Identifying the health and economic consequences of water- and sanitation-related illnesses; costs and benefits of curative and preventative interventions. Interpreting data related to epidemiological and environmental concepts. No previous experience in engineering is required.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-AQR", "GER:DB-EngrAppSci", "WAY-SMA"],"id":210763,"primary":[[{"primary-instructors":[],"secondary-instructors":["Davis, J."],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"1:30:00 PM","end":"2:50:00 PM","instructors":["Davis, J."],"location":""}],"id":28466}],[],[]],"primary_type":"Introsem"}}